In article <WCS.94Apr27050142@anchor.att.com>,
Bill Stewart +1-510-484-6204 <wcs@anchor.ho.att.com> wrote:
|In article <xkzvTlt.allentaylor@delphi.com| Allen Taylor <allentaylor@delphi.com| writes:
|   CNN has just announced at 2130 Hours EST [2-26-94] that RSA has been broken
|   by a brute force effor of 1600 Computers over an eight month period.
|   Film at 11'.....
|Either you or they got it wrong - RSA-129 has been broken, not RSA.
|RSA-129 is one 129-digit N=P*Q combination, which has now been factored.
|(Yee-hah!  Good work, folks!)  Total work was about 8000 MIPS-years,
|if I remember the number right.  So that suggests that if you use a
|384-bit RSA key, the NSA or a bunch of volunteers could break it in a
|few months.  If you use 512-bit, you're probably safe for now.
|1024-bit is fine.
|
\\\\\\
I think it shows something more - that simple number theoretic coding
schemes are inherently vulnerable to advances in number theoretic 
algorithms as well as computing systems.
D.H.


